    'acp-op-ae-op-deploy-packages': {
        title: 'Deploy Software Packages from AssetExplorer Tickets',
        content: `
            <h3>Description</h3>
            <p>Technicians can deploy custom software packages (created in Application Control Plus) to managed endpoints directly from within <strong>AssetExplorer</strong> tickets. This streamlines software provisioning without requiring access to the Application Control Plus console.</p>

            <h3>How This Works</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Software packages are pre-configured in Application Control Plus under Software Deployment → Packages.</li>
                <li>From a AssetExplorer ticket, the technician selects the <strong>"Deploy Package"</strong> action for the associated asset.</li>
                <li>A list of available packages from Application Control Plus is shown. The technician selects and confirms.</li>
                <li>The package is pushed to the endpoint via the Application Control Plus agent and installed silently.</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Prerequisites</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Software packages must be created and approved in Application Control Plus.</li>
                <li>The endpoint agent must be online for immediate deployment; offline agents receive the deployment on next check-in.</li>
                <li>Integration must be active between Application Control Plus and AssetExplorer.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Known Limitations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Only pre-configured packages in Application Control Plus are available — custom EXE/MSI files cannot be uploaded directly from AssetExplorer.</li>
                <li>Deployment to groups of machines is not supported from AssetExplorer — only per-ticket asset deployment.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Logs for Troubleshooting</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Application Control Plus server:</strong> <code>&lt;Install_Dir&gt;/logs/swdeploy.log</code></li>
                <li><strong>Agent side:</strong> <code>&lt;Agent_Dir&gt;/logs/dcswdeplog.txt</code></li>
            </ul>
            
        `,
        links: []
    },
    'acp-op-ae-op-deploy-templates': {
        title: 'Deploy Configuration Templates from AssetExplorer Tickets',
        content: `
            <h3>Description</h3>
            <p>This feature allows technicians to push pre-defined <strong>configuration templates</strong> (e.g., wallpaper, browser settings, power settings, shortcuts) from <strong>AssetExplorer</strong> to managed endpoints. Templates are created in Application Control Plus and made available through the integration.</p>

            <h3>How This Works</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Configuration templates are created in Application Control Plus under Configuration → Templates.</li>
                <li>From a AssetExplorer ticket, the technician selects <strong>"Deploy Template"</strong> for the associated asset.</li>
                <li>A list of available templates is fetched from Application Control Plus. The technician selects and deploys.</li>
                <li>The configuration is applied to the endpoint by the Application Control Plus agent.</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Prerequisites</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Configuration templates must be created in Application Control Plus.</li>
                <li>The endpoint agent must be online for immediate deployment.</li>
                <li>Integration between Application Control Plus and AssetExplorer must be active.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Known Limitations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Only templates pre-configured in Application Control Plus are available.</li>
                <li>Some templates may require a reboot to take full effect.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Logs for Troubleshooting</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Application Control Plus server:</strong> <code>&lt;Install_Dir&gt;/logs/configdeploy.log</code></li>
                <li><strong>Agent side:</strong> <code>&lt;Agent_Dir&gt;/logs/dcconfig.log</code></li>
            </ul>
            
        `,
        links: []
    },
    'acp-op-ae-op-iframe': {
        title: 'Load Application Control Plus iFrame in AssetExplorer',
        content: `
            <h3>Description</h3>
            <p>This feature embeds the full <strong>Application Control Plus</strong> web console inside <strong>AssetExplorer</strong> as an iFrame. Technicians can access Application Control Plus features without leaving the AssetExplorer interface, reducing context-switching and improving productivity.</p>

            <h3>How This Works</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Once the integration is configured, the Application Control Plus module appears as a tab or section within the AssetExplorer console.</li>
                <li>Clicking the tab loads the Application Control Plus web interface inside an iFrame within the AssetExplorer page.</li>
                <li>Technicians can navigate Application Control Plus features, view reports, and perform actions — all within the AssetExplorer browser session.</li>
                <li>Authentication is handled via the integration's API key/token, so separate login is not required.</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Prerequisites</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Both Application Control Plus and AssetExplorer servers must be reachable from the technician's browser.</li>
                <li>Integration must be configured with valid API credentials.</li>
                <li>If using HTTPS, both products must have valid SSL certificates. Mixed content (HTTP inside HTTPS) will be blocked by browsers.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Known Limitations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>If the Application Control Plus server has <code>X-Frame-Options</code> set to DENY or SAMEORIGIN, the iFrame will not load. This header may need to be adjusted.</li>
                <li>Browser security policies may block cross-origin iFrames if the domains differ significantly.</li>
                <li>Performance may be slightly slower than directly accessing the Application Control Plus console, as the page is loaded within another page.</li>
                <li>Some browser extensions (ad blockers, privacy tools) may interfere with iFrame loading.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Logs for Troubleshooting</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Check the <strong>browser developer console</strong> (F12 → Console tab) for Content Security Policy (CSP) or X-Frame-Options errors.</li>
                <li><strong>Application Control Plus server:</strong> <code>&lt;Install_Dir&gt;/logs/serverout.txt</code> for access/authentication errors.</li>
                <li>Ensure both servers use the same protocol (both HTTP or both HTTPS).</li>
            </ul>
            
        `,
        links: []
    },
