    'rap-op-snow-basic-op-remote-control': {
        title: 'Remote Control from ServiceNow Tickets',
        content: `
            <h3>Description</h3>
            <p>This feature allows technicians to launch a remote desktop connection to any managed endpoint directly from within <strong>ServiceNow</strong>. Instead of switching between consoles, technicians can resolve issues faster by accessing the machine while viewing the ticket.</p>

            <h3>How This Works</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>When a technician opens a ticket in ServiceNow that has an associated asset managed by Remote Access Plus, a <strong>"Remote Control"</strong> action button appears.</li>
                <li>Clicking the button sends a request to the Remote Access Plus server via API, which initiates a remote session to the endpoint's agent.</li>
                <li>The remote viewer opens in a new browser tab or the native remote tool, providing full desktop access.</li>
                <li>Session details (start time, duration, technician) are logged for audit purposes.</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Prerequisites</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>The Remote Access Plus agent must be installed and online on the target machine.</li>
                <li>Remote Access Plus and ServiceNow integration must be configured and active.</li>
                <li>The technician must have remote control permissions in Remote Access Plus.</li>
                <li>Ports required for remote control (typically 8020, 8443) must be open between the technician's browser and the Remote Access Plus server.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Known Limitations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Only computers that have the Remote Access Plus agent installed and reporting will be available for remote control.</li>
                <li>If the endpoint is offline or unreachable, the remote session cannot be established.</li>
                <li>Pop-up blockers may prevent the remote viewer from launching in a new tab.</li>
                <li>Some VPN configurations may block the required ports.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Logs for Troubleshooting</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Remote Access Plus server:</strong> <code>&lt;Install_Dir&gt;/logs/remotecontrol.log</code></li>
                <li><strong>Agent side:</strong> <code>&lt;Agent_Dir&gt;/logs/rcgateway.log</code></li>
                <li>Check browser console for pop-up blocker errors.</li>
                <li>Verify the agent is online under Remote Access Plus → Scope of Management.</li>
            </ul>
            
        `,
        links: []
    },
    'rap-op-snow-basic-owner-assign': {
        title: 'Auto-Assign Last Logged-In User as Asset Owner',
        content: `
            <h3>Description</h3>
            <p>This feature automatically maps the <strong>last logged-in user</strong> detected by the Remote Access Plus agent to the corresponding asset in <strong>ServiceNow</strong>, setting them as the asset owner. This helps keep the asset-owner mapping current without manual updates.</p>

            <h3>How This Works</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>The Remote Access Plus agent detects the currently logged-in user on the endpoint during each scan.</li>
                <li>When the inventory data is synced to ServiceNow, the "last logged-in user" field is included.</li>
                <li>If Auto-Assign is enabled, ServiceNow automatically updates the asset owner to match this user.</li>
                <li>If the user is not found in ServiceNow's user directory, the mapping may be skipped or a new user record may be created (depending on configuration).</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Prerequisites</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Inventory asset sync between Remote Access Plus and ServiceNow must be active.</li>
                <li>The "Auto-assign users" option must be enabled in the integration feature settings.</li>
                <li>User records should exist in ServiceNow for the mapping to work correctly.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Known Limitations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Only the <strong>last logged-in user</strong> is assigned — shared or multi-user machines may have frequently changing owners.</li>
                <li>Service accounts or system accounts that log in may be incorrectly mapped if not filtered out.</li>
                <li>The user must exist in ServiceNow's user database for the assignment to succeed.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Logs for Troubleshooting</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Remote Access Plus server:</strong> <code>&lt;Install_Dir&gt;/logs/sdpintegration.txt</code></li>
                <li>Search for "auto-assign" or "owner" in the integration log.</li>
                <li>Verify the user record exists in ServiceNow under User Management.</li>
            </ul>
            
        `,
        links: []
    },
    'rap-op-snow-sgc-asset-removal': {
        title: 'Asset Removal Sync to ServiceNow – Remote Access Plus',
        content: `
            <h3>Description</h3>
            <p>When a device is removed from the <strong>Scope of Management (SoM)</strong> in <strong>Remote Access Plus</strong>, this feature updates or removes the corresponding <strong>Configuration Item (CI)</strong> in <strong>ServiceNow's CMDB</strong>. This keeps the CMDB clean by removing stale entries for decommissioned devices.</p>

            <h3>How This Works</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>A device is removed from Remote Access Plus's Scope of Management (via uninstall, decommission, etc.).</li>
                <li>Remote Access Plus sends a removal notification to ServiceNow via REST API.</li>
                <li>Based on configuration, the CI in ServiceNow is either deleted, retired, or marked as decommissioned.</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Prerequisites</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>ServiceNow integration must be configured and active in Remote Access Plus.</li>
                <li>The asset must have been previously synced to ServiceNow.</li>
                <li>The ServiceNow service account must have CI write/delete permissions.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Known Limitations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>If the integration is down at removal time, the action will not be retroactively sent.</li>
                <li>Bulk removals may be rate-limited by ServiceNow's API.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Logs for Troubleshooting</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Remote Access Plus server:</strong> <code>&lt;Install_Dir&gt;/logs/snowintegration.log</code></li>
                <li>Search for "removal" or "delete" in the integration log.</li>
            </ul>
            
        `,
        links: []
    },
