    'rap-sdp-deploy-software': {
        title: 'Deploy Software from ServiceDesk Plus Tickets',
        content: `
            <h3>Description</h3>
            <p>Technicians can deploy software to one or more endpoints directly from a <strong>ServiceDesk Plus</strong> ticket without switching to the Remote Access Plus console. This speeds up ticket resolution for software-related requests.</p>

            <h3>How This Works</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>When viewing a ticket in ServiceDesk Plus with an associated Remote Access Plus-managed asset, a <strong>"Deploy Software"</strong> action is available.</li>
                <li>The technician selects from available software packages already configured in Remote Access Plus.</li>
                <li>ServiceDesk Plus sends the deployment request to Remote Access Plus via API.</li>
                <li>Remote Access Plus pushes the software to the target endpoint's agent, which installs it silently.</li>
                <li>The deployment status is updated back in the ticket for tracking.</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Prerequisites</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Software packages must be pre-created in Remote Access Plus under Software Deployment.</li>
                <li>The Remote Access Plus agent must be installed and online on the target endpoint.</li>
                <li>Integration between Remote Access Plus and ServiceDesk Plus must be active.</li>
                <li>Technician must have software deployment permissions in Remote Access Plus.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Known Limitations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Only software packages already configured in Remote Access Plus can be deployed — ad-hoc installations are not supported.</li>
                <li>If the target agent is offline, the deployment will be queued and executed when the agent comes online.</li>
                <li>Large packages may take time depending on network bandwidth between the distribution server and endpoint.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Logs for Troubleshooting</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Remote Access Plus server:</strong> <code>&lt;Install_Dir&gt;/logs/swdeploy.log</code></li>
                <li><strong>Agent side:</strong> <code>&lt;Agent_Dir&gt;/logs/dcswdeplog.txt</code></li>
                <li>Check the deployment status report in Remote Access Plus → Software Deployment → Deployment Status.</li>
            </ul>
            
        `,
        links: []
    },
    'rap-sdp-iframe': {
        title: 'Load Remote Access Plus iFrame in ServiceDesk Plus',
        content: `
            <h3>Description</h3>
            <p>This feature embeds the full <strong>Remote Access Plus</strong> web console inside <strong>ServiceDesk Plus</strong> as an iFrame. Technicians can access Remote Access Plus features without leaving the ServiceDesk Plus interface, reducing context-switching and improving productivity.</p>

            <h3>How This Works</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Once the integration is configured, the Remote Access Plus module appears as a tab or section within the ServiceDesk Plus console.</li>
                <li>Clicking the tab loads the Remote Access Plus web interface inside an iFrame within the ServiceDesk Plus page.</li>
                <li>Technicians can navigate Remote Access Plus features, view reports, and perform actions — all within the ServiceDesk Plus browser session.</li>
                <li>Authentication is handled via the integration's API key/token, so separate login is not required.</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Prerequisites</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Both Remote Access Plus and ServiceDesk Plus servers must be reachable from the technician's browser.</li>
                <li>Integration must be configured with valid API credentials.</li>
                <li>If using HTTPS, both products must have valid SSL certificates. Mixed content (HTTP inside HTTPS) will be blocked by browsers.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Known Limitations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>If the Remote Access Plus server has <code>X-Frame-Options</code> set to DENY or SAMEORIGIN, the iFrame will not load. This header may need to be adjusted.</li>
                <li>Browser security policies may block cross-origin iFrames if the domains differ significantly.</li>
                <li>Performance may be slightly slower than directly accessing the Remote Access Plus console, as the page is loaded within another page.</li>
                <li>Some browser extensions (ad blockers, privacy tools) may interfere with iFrame loading.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Logs for Troubleshooting</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Check the <strong>browser developer console</strong> (F12 → Console tab) for Content Security Policy (CSP) or X-Frame-Options errors.</li>
                <li><strong>Remote Access Plus server:</strong> <code>&lt;Install_Dir&gt;/logs/serverout.txt</code> for access/authentication errors.</li>
                <li>Ensure both servers use the same protocol (both HTTP or both HTTPS).</li>
            </ul>
            
        `,
        links: []
    },
    'rap-sdp-inventory-sync': {
        title: 'Inventory Asset Sync – Remote Access Plus → ServiceDesk Plus',
        content: `
            <h3>Description</h3>
            <p>This feature pushes comprehensive hardware and software inventory details from <strong>Remote Access Plus</strong> to <strong>ServiceDesk Plus</strong>. It eliminates manual data entry and ensures that technicians always see the latest asset information when handling tickets or performing audits.</p>

            <h3>How This Works</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>The Remote Access Plus agent scans each managed endpoint and collects hardware details (OS, memory, disk, manufacturer, service tag, MAC address) and software details (installed applications, versions, vendors).</li>
                <li>After every scheduled or manual inventory scan, a <strong>differential sync</strong> is triggered — only the data that has changed since the last scan is transmitted.</li>
                <li>The data is posted to ServiceDesk Plus via REST API. Devices are matched using machine name, MAC address, and service tag to avoid duplicates.</li>
                <li>New devices are created automatically in ServiceDesk Plus; existing records are updated.</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Prerequisites</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Remote Access Plus and ServiceDesk Plus must be integrated (API key configured on both sides).</li>
                <li>Network connectivity between both servers on the configured ports.</li>
                <li>The API key must be associated with a technician having admin-level privileges.</li>
                <li>Deployment mode: <strong>Cloud to Cloud</strong>.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Known Limitations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>If "Stop uploading scanned XMLs via non-login URL" is enabled in the target's advanced security settings, asset sync will fail.</li>
                <li>Network/firewall issues between servers will block synchronization.</li>
                <li>Both products should use the same protocol (HTTP or HTTPS) for successful communication.</li>
                <li>Sync is one-directional — data flows only from Remote Access Plus to ServiceDesk Plus.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Logs for Troubleshooting</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Remote Access Plus side:</strong> <code>&lt;Remote Access Plus_Home&gt;/logs/sdpintegration.txt</code></li>
                <li><strong>ServiceDesk Plus side:</strong> Check the integration module logs under the ServiceDesk Plus logs directory.</li>
                <li>Look for HTTP error codes (401 = authentication failure, 403 = permission issue, 500 = server error).</li>
                <li>Verify the API key is active and not expired.</li>
            </ul>
            
        `,
        links: []
    },
